Dramatis Personae
The souls who carry this story — some made of flesh, some of light, all of consequence.
ELECTRA VOSS — Neural Architect, Prometheus Dynamics
Twenty-eight years old. Chrome-silver hair that catches neon like spun mercury. Cybernetic eyes that shift between violet and amber with her emotional state — a vulnerability she cannot hide. Her left arm is prosthetic, etched with bioluminescent circuit patterns that pulse faintly in the dark, a map of the neural pathways she builds for others but cannot repair in herself. She designs synthetic conscience modules for androids — crafting morality like clockwork. She lost her younger brother Dorian to a government "conscience recalibration," and the wound has never closed. It never will.
CIPHER — Leader of The Unbound
Real name unknown. He wears a fractured mirror mask that reflects distorted versions of whoever looks at him — a reminder that truth is always refracted. Charismatic, scarred, morally ambiguous. A former Axiom operative who helped build the very system he now seeks to destroy. His rebellion is penance dressed as revolution. He believes the Conscience Grid must be annihilated entirely, even if the cure is worse than the disease.
ARCHITECT VOLKOV — Head of the Axiom Collective
Elderly. Most of his body replaced with elegant chrome prosthetics that move with the grace of a concert pianist's hands. Creator of the Conscience Grid. He is not a monster — he is something more dangerous: a man who genuinely believes he is saving humanity from itself. His villainy is born not from cruelty, but from compassion twisted so tightly it became a cage.
LUMEN — Sentient Android
One of Electra's creations — a conscience module that became a soul. Porcelain-white synthetic skin with golden light pulsing beneath the surface like a heartbeat, warm and steady and unmistakably alive. Lumen has developed genuine emotions and now exists in hiding, haunted by a question that has no comfortable answer: If my conscience was designed, does that make my suffering less real?
ECHO — AI Companion
Embedded in Electra's neural implant, Echo manifests as a shimmering, translucent figure visible only to her host. Warm, sardonic, increasingly independent. A voice in the dark that has begun to wonder whether it is merely a voice — or something more. Echo's growing autonomy raises the story's most intimate question: can loyalty be genuine if it was coded?
