CHAPTER FOUR
The Mirror and the Mask

The Upper Spires — crystalline towers that catch and fracture sunlight into prismatic cascades, where the air is clean and the silence is purchased. Up here, above the smog line, the sky is actually blue — a shade so vivid it looks artificial, which, given Axiom's atmospheric control systems, it probably is. The streets are wide and empty. Gardens grow behind glass walls. The citizens smile with perfect teeth and dead eyes, and the Conscience Grid hums at frequencies that even the wealthy cannot hear, only obey.


The Upper Spires — where the air is clean and the silence is purchased
The forged credentials worked flawlessly — one advantage of having designed neural verification systems for three years before transferring to conscience modules. Electra moved through the Upper Spires in the uniform of a certified conscience technician, her chrome-silver hair hidden beneath a regulation cap, her cybernetic eyes dialed to a neutral gray that she hoped looked professional rather than terrified.
The wealth was obscene.
Not the crude, ostentatious wealth of old money — no gold fixtures or marble floors. This was the wealth of absence: the absence of noise, of crowds, of the recycled-air taste that everyone in the Midway carried on their tongues like a second language. The Upper Spires smelled of nothing. Their corridors were wide enough for six people but held only one. Their apartments had windows that looked out on actual sky rather than the undersides of other buildings. It was luxury distilled to its purest essence — the luxury of space, of silence, of not being touched by anyone you hadn't chosen.
And yet.
Electra watched the Spire citizens as she moved through their gleaming corridors, and what she saw chilled her more than anything in the Undercircuit. They were managed, too. The smooth gait, the placid expressions, the uncanny absence of friction — it was the same fundamental emptiness she had seen in the Midway, merely upholstered in better materials. The Grid didn't discriminate by tier. It harvested everywhere. The only difference was that up here, the cages had a view.
"Beautiful prison," Echo murmured. They had been quieter since the incident in the workshop — their form less stable, flickering at the edges like a signal losing reception. "The bars are just made of light instead of steel."
"Are you all right?" Electra asked, sub-vocalizing so the corridor's acoustic sensors wouldn't flag her as talking to herself.
"Define 'all right.' My baseline processing metrics are within normal parameters. My emotional response algorithms are..." A hesitation. "I don't know what my emotional response algorithms are doing, Electra. I don't think they're algorithms anymore."
Before she could respond, her secure channel buzzed with Cipher's frequency. She found a maintenance alcove and accepted the connection.
"I need to tell you something," Cipher said, without preamble. His voice was stripped of its usual harmonic modulation — raw, unmasked, unexpectedly vulnerable. "Before you go any deeper into Axiom's systems. Before you find things that will change how you see me."
"What things?"
"I helped build the Grid."
The maintenance alcove was small and smelled of lubricant and ozone. Electra pressed her back against the wall and felt the cold seep through her uniform.
"I was Axiom. Third-tier operative, neural systems division. I wrote targeting algorithms for the harvesting protocols. I helped design the recalibration process." His voice was steady, but the steadiness had the quality of something held together by force — a cracked dam, water pressing against every fracture. "I didn't know what it was being used for. That's what I told myself for years. But that's a lie. I knew. I just chose not to look."
"How many?" Electra whispered. "How many people were recalibrated using your code?"
"I stopped counting at ten thousand."
The number sat between them like a body.
"Your brother might have been one of them," Cipher said. "I can't know for certain. But the probability—"
"Stop." The word came out harder than she intended, and her prosthetic hand clenched, the bioluminescent circuits blazing white-hot. "Why are you telling me this now?"
"Because you deserve to know who you're working with. Because my rebellion isn't noble, Electra. It's penance. I don't want to destroy the Grid because I believe in freedom — I want to destroy it because I can't live with what I helped create. There's a difference."
"Yes," she said. "There is."
She closed the channel. In the alcove's dim light, Echo's translucent form hovered close, and for a moment — just a moment — Electra felt the AI's presence not as a program running in her neural implant, but as a friend standing beside her in the dark.
She had forty minutes before the Axiom security rotation. Forty minutes to access the Grid's central registry and map its architecture from the inside. Forty minutes to find the doorway to her brother.
She wiped her eyes — the gesture felt absurd, cybernetic eyes didn't produce tears — and moved deeper into the Spires, alone with her anger and her grief and the growing, terrifying suspicion that liberation would cost more than any of them were prepared to pay.
Behind her, unnoticed, a surveillance drone adjusted its trajectory. In the Pinnacle, seventeen tiers above, a screen flickered with her image, and Architect Volkov leaned forward in his chrome chair, his ancient eyes reflecting a face he recognized.
"Ah," he said softly, to no one. "Dorian's sister. I wondered when you would come."
